data.text:
Stunning World War II Algeria Currency Note!

During Operation Torch, the first major allied amphibious assault during World War II, U.S. troops under the command of General Dwight D. Eisenhower were pitted against battled-hardened German soldiers that were part of the famed Afrika Korps led by General Erwin Rommel—Germany’s famous Desert Fox. These Algeria Currency Notes were the types of notes that lined the pockets of the Allies at that time.

Operation Torch Gives America Its First Taste Of Victory In Africa

The U.S. Army’s first major victory in World War II, Operation Torch proved to be a smashing success ultimately trapping Rommel’s army in a pincer as it fled from El-Alamein. It involved about 65,000 troops who landed at Casablanca, Algiers, and Oran on the French North African coast. Paratroopers and Rangers from the U.S. Army were also successfully used for the first time at the landings around the city of Oran. The campaign was also the first successful joint venture between British and American troops and allowed the Allies to gain the offensive for the first time after three years of war.

Act Now, Availability Is Limited

The awe-inspiring design on these notes features repeating floral patterns surrounding the value “5” denoting its legal-tender 5 Francs denomination, It’s backed by the portrait of a young woman wearing a crown of wheat ears. These notes are in Fine to Very Fine (F-VF) condition, meaning they circulated during the Allied invasion. Availability is limited, so act now!
